text:
My worry with returning to restaurants, particularly when I don't indulge in them often, is that they won't live up to my memory. Zahav has not failed me yet. What an awesome Restaurant Week dinner.

I love being greeted with good pickled vegetables and Zahav's (turnip?, carrot, and onion) is better than any found at any Chinese restaurant I've dined at.

Hummus (my favorite ever, and now available at Dizengoff!) paired with laffa (fluffy, piping hot, and delicious!) and six salatim dishes:
- Eggplant, decadent, thick, and stew-like;
- Beets, an exemplar of creamy goodness;
- Pickled cucumbers and tomatoes, refreshing, though without the punch of those that started the table;
- Carrots, somehow baked in a manner that I actually liked (not generally a carrot fan);
- Pickled onions, sharp and flavorful; and
- Tabbouleh, normally well-loved, this was my least favorite offering of the salatim as it happened to be slightly unbalanced (heavy on the parsley).

Mezze:
- Roasted brussel sprouts, loved the Bulgarian feta--lots of zing, and plenty salty, though I wasn't a fan of the pickled lemon, which was so tart that it simply overwhelmed the palate;
- Yemenite beef stew, meat so tender it basically melted in one's mouth;
- Fried fingerling potatoes, definitely needed the kashkaval cheese, anchovy, and shifka peppers to elevate it from feeling everyday humdrum;
- Fried cauliflower, 'nough said (a dinner mate who dislikes cauliflower actually liked this preparation!);
- Crispy lamb's tongue, smelled like bacon, nicely crispy--enjoyed the apples the tongue was paired with; and
- Grilled duck hearts, too gamey and texturally unpleasant for my taste (a bit squishy and rubbery at the same time), though the dinner mate who ordered it said they were cooked perfectly: not overdone.

Al Ha'esh:
- Kofte, quite spicy and overall nice flavors;
- Lamb merguez, tender and savory: loved the textural variation of the pepitas (i.e., pumpkin seeds)

Dessert:
- The coffee mousse was divine: so rich, creamy, and perfectly paired with the huckleberries;
- The pear sorbet was the coffee mousse's equal: refreshing and perfectly paired with the sweet, crunchy granola.

Our server and assistants were all lovely and as always the restaurant itself has a great atmosphere: would really like to take one of the farmhouse-style tables for my home!
